\begin_layout Abstract
This paper establishes a Real-Time imaging strategy for the AARTFAAC Image
 domain Radio transient detector.
 We first establish the operational constraints for fast synthesis imaging,
 and then establish our imaging strategy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Keywords
Low-Frequency Imaging, Radio Transients, Synthesis Imaging
\end_layout

\begin_layout Keywords
\begin_inset Note Greyedout
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Paper overall flow:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Introduction to imaging requirements from the generic point of view of transient
 detection in the image domain.
 Transient detection figure of merit, role of field of view Vs.
 sensitivity, why it makes sense to build a low sensitivity, wide-field
 instrument.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Generic introduction to the AARTFAAC, different modes of operation (short
 term, snapshot imaging and longer term, more sensitive imaging) and effect
 of each from the imaging point of view
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Quantifying transient detection sensitivity? A single figure of merit for
 transient detection with the AARTFAAC.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Distinguish between 2 perspectives:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Given the instrumental configuration, how can we extract the best individual
 snapshots from it, and how close are we to doing this?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Given that main aim is real-time transient detection and the presence of
 previous time samples, which parameters can we optimize for the best transient
 detection performance?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
How best can we utilize the time axis instead of treating it as a snapshot
 generator?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Introduction to the TraP transient detection algo, role expected to be played
 by the imager, interfacing with TraP
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Problem statement and remainder paper layout.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The AARTFAAC as an All-Sky imaging transient detector.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Advantages of the AARTFAAC for transient detection.
 Zenith pointing, snapshot mode, almost fully filled aperture, field of
 view, continuous imaging.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Expected theoretical point source sensitivity, confusion limit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Effect of wide field imaging, quantifying distortion to source fluxes due
 to array projection effects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Identification of the most crucial parameters influencing imaging from AARTFAAC
 specifically from the transient detection perspective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Difference imaging (? here or in calib paper? Separate section?)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Various possible array configurations, effect on PSF, point source sensitivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Wideband imaging, choice of subbands from increasing UV coverage point of
 view.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Optimal imaging from the AARTFAAC
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Choice of gridding algorithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
optimal weighting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Choice of deconvolution algorithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Choice of level (in terms of number of sources) to which to deconvolve,
 given observed noise characteristics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
facetted imaging for full fov flux recovery, choice of number of facets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Flux calibration in image domain (Not in calibration paper?)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Primary beam model, PBCORR
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Generating high sensitivity images via wide band/time stacking.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Behaviour of noise as a function of fov, effect of PBCORR, gridding deconvolutio
n.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Computing performance, can we tradeoff transient detection sensitivity for
 computing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Diffuse emission modelling for optimising transient detection.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Can we do a better spatial filtering than a visibility cutoff?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If calibration uses a visibility cutoff, can we put back filtered visibilities
 and/or use a different filtering to reduce sidelobes?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
AARTFAAC imaging performance under various operating conditions
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Flux stability of calibrator sources over time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Day/night time transient FoM comparison
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Reliably imaged fraction of FoV.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Any ionospheric refraction that we can measure? Will require bright source
 position and flux estimation...
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In how many ways can the imaging go bad, needed due to automated, stand-alone
 operation requirement (Ant's quality control document).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Number and kind of image streams to generate (1 sec/16 sec.
 images?)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Store calibrated/raw visibilities in lookback buffer? (More TraP related)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Imaging pipeline implementation description (Unless Folkert is writing that
 up separately...).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Generating local coord.
 images or RA/Dec, for interfacing with TraP.
